Analysis & Trends of Twitch Games

Alex Van, Rana Odeh, Garret Shen

Introduction:¶

We know and understand games to be a focal point of the entertainment industry. Whether you enjoy playing video games, or watching others play video games, games are a great way to relax and have fun with friends or family. Twitch is one of the growing platforms that allows users to watch other people live play games/chat (more discussion presented later). While not as relevant to certain individuals, we believe that analyzing trends in Twitch as well as popular games can gain a better understanding of the growing game industry as a whole. Specifically, we are studying the increase in average viewer count for popular games. This study allows us to understand what the gaming community comes to love and enjoy watching.

This tutorial/study guides us through 5 steps of data science analysis:
1) Data Collection
2) Data Processing
3) Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization 4) Model: Analysis, Hypothesis testing, and ML 5) Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

What Is Twitch?

<img src = "https://1000logos.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Twitch-logo.png" alt="Twitch Logo", width = "100", height="100">

Released in 2011, Twitch is a streaming platform for all users to watch or hold live content for viewers to watch. In terms of what content is hosted on Twitch, lots of users mainly stream and watch video games (conventional or Esports related). However, there can be other categories such as podcasts or hangouts where streamers can collaborate and hangout with their viewers.

Purpose

We understand that not everyone's interest is towards games and watching games. However, we wanted to pick a topic that motivated us and interested us to the best of our abilities. We also wanted to make sure the study was simple and easy to understand.

Data Collection:¶

The first stage of the data science cycle is data collection. The data in which we collected can be found on kaggle, which is helpful for finding any databases in general. We decided to obviously choose a twitch data set: this set contains two data frames. The first dataframe is one that describes the most popular games on twitch from the years 2016-2023. The second data frame contains statistics for the overall views and information of Twitch from 2016-2023. The second data set is a generic gaming dataset. This dataset contains one dataframe that tells us popular games as a whole from 1980-2023.

Using python imports as well as Pandas read_csv method, we are able to read in multiple csv files. The sources to the csv files are linked below.

Sources:¶

Twitch Dataset: Evolution of Top Games on Twitch
Game Dataset: Popular Video Games 1980 - 2023

Data Processing:¶

The next stage in the data science process and of this study is data processing. Now that we have the data, we need to process and clean this data so it can be useable for future uses of our study and visualization. What we consider as clean data is to remove any unnecessary information (this can be columns, or missing/Nan values). In addition, we can use certain libraries we have imported to our advantage of cleaning and processing this data. Libraries such as Pandas and NumPy are notable and helpful libraries. These libraries contain methods crucial for processing data.

Notably for this project, we want to clean data from our three dataframes that we have collected, for example, we can remove the reviews from our games dataframe, as we will not be needing that.

# This is a method to modify the column of the twitch_games dataframe.
def modify_twitch_game_col(df):
    
    # I want to rewrite the date column for clarity
    df['Date'] = df.apply(lambda row: pd.Period(year=row['Year'], month=row['Month'], freq='M'), axis=1)
    
    # Delete the month and year columns
    del df['Month']
    del df['Year']
    
    # Reorder the columns
    reorder = ["Rank", "Date", "Game", "Hours_watched", "Hours_streamed", "Peak_viewers", "Peak_channels", "Streamers", "Avg_viewers", "Avg_channels", "Avg_viewer_ratio"]
    df = df.reindex(columns = reorder)
    
    # Rename the columns
    rename = {"Hours_watched": "Hours Watched", "Hours_streamed": "Hours Streamed", "Peak_viewers": "Maximum Viewers", "Peak_channels": "Maximum Channels", "Streamers": "Number of Streamers", 
              "Avg_viewers": "Average Viewer Count", "Avg_channels": "Average Channel Count", "Avg_viewer_ratio": "Average Viewer Ratio"}
    df = df.rename(columns = rename)
    
    return df
In [14]:
def modify_twitch_global_col(df):
    
    # Rewrite the date column
    df['Date'] = df.apply(lambda row: pd.Period(year=row['year'], month=row['Month'], freq='M'), axis=1)
    
    # Reorder the columns
    reorder = ["Date", "Hours_watched", "Avg_viewers", "Peak_viewers", "Streams", "Avg_channels", "Games_streamed", "Viewer_ratio"]
    df = df.reindex(columns = reorder)
    
    # Rename the columns
    rename = {"Hours_watched": "Hours Watched", "Peak_viewers": "Maximum Viewers", "Streams": "Number of Streames", 
              "Avg_viewers": "Average Viewer Count", "Avg_channels": "Average Channel Count", "Viewer_ratio": "Average Viewer Ratio",
             "Games_streamed": "Number of Games Streamed"}
    df = df.rename(columns = rename)
    
    return df
In [15]:
months = {"Jan": 1, "Feb": 2, "Mar": 3, "Apr": 4, "May": 5, "Jun": 6, "Jul": 7, "Aug": 8, "Sep": 9, "Oct":10,
         "Nov": 11, "Dec": 12}

def modify_games_col(df):
    
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        
        year_data = row['Release Date'][len(row['Release Date'])-5:]
        month_word = row['Release Date'][:3]
    
        # Check if the month is in the dictionary, As well we want data from 2016 and over.
        if month_word in months:
            # Convert the month to the corresponding numeric value
            month_num = months[month_word]
        
            # Convert the release date to pd.Period()
            df.at[index, 'Release Date'] = pd.Period(year=int(year_data), month=month_num, freq='M')
        else:
            df = df.drop(index)
    
    # Lets now remove the unecessary columns
    del df['Unnamed: 0']
    del df['Times Listed']
    del df['Summary']
    del df['Reviews']
    del df['Playing']
    del df['Backlogs']
    
    rename = {"Title": "Game"}
    df = df.rename(columns = rename)
    
    # Rearrange Columns
    reorder = ["Release Date", "Game", "Rating", "Number of Reviews", "Plays", "Wishlist", "Team", "Genres"]
    df = df.reindex(columns = reorder)

    return df

Now that we have all three dataframes, we can also create another data frame that merges the games that have been popular on twitch (df_twitch_games), and the global games dataframe (df_games). We can see the overlap between the two by setting its property to inner.

Inner means that when merging, we only show columns that intersect each other.
Outer is the opposite, meaning when we merge, we show all values whether they intersect or do not intersect each other.

Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization:¶

The next step of the data science process and of this study is to visually analyze the data and dataframes we have merged/created. We can use the Matlabplot library, seaborn, or other Python graphing libraries to achieve this. This part of the process allows us to use the information we have gotten to visualize and predict future outcomes.

Lets now use our second dataframe (not the merged one) to create a graph. Lets create a graph of the number of hours watched on Twitch over time using Matlabplot Library.

In [21]:
# This converts the 'Date' column in our dataframe to a datetime format. This is done to make sure that we are able to plot
# The date (since they are in Y-M format) which would not work to plot. 
df_twitch_global["Date"] = df_twitch_global["Date"].astype("datetime64")

Awesome! just by using the code presented above we are able to see the data come to life. From this plot we can tell so much about this data that we would not have been able to tell as quickly if we did not plot it. For example, based on this plot, we can see that throughout 2016-2023 there is a general increase in the total hours watched on Twitch. This indicates that there is a growing popularity of the platform over the years. In addition, another very important aspect that we can gather from this plot is that there is a sharp increase in hours watched around 2020. This was during the time of the global COVID-19 pandemic, which shows us that while people were under lockdown they used streaming platforms such as Twitch for entertainment.

Just from this one graph we were able to gather so much information! Now lets move on to graphing different parts of the data so we can get even more information (So much fun!).

How cool! Instead of having to write up code and printing out each individual plot in your notebook we can print out several subplots at the same time and see such different data and information all at once!

These subplots show us the trend of hours watched, average viewer count, maximum viewers, number of streamers, average channel count and average viewer ratio. With these subplots we can look at each individual one and even compare them to each other to gather data and information. For example, we can see in the Hours Watched plot that the number of hours seemed to increase significantly until about early 2022 and then starts to fluctuate with a slight downward trend. It is known that after 2022 is when all the things with COVID start to slow down and people start to go back into their normal life routine. So, this shows us as people started to get out of quarantine, they stopped using Twitch as much as they did when they were in quarantine. From all of these plots combined, we can see that there was a growth phase from 2016-2021 with a stable decline from 2021-2024.

Note: Plotting your data is something that is so important because you will be able to physically SEE the trends rather than having to look at tables and figure out what the trend is just by numbers. After we gather this information, it can be used in so many ways such as maintaining or reviving growth of the platform, data could be applied to improve user engagement tactics, focused marketing campaigns, and perhaps even diversify content offerings.

Model: Analysis, Hypothesis testing, and ML:¶

The next step of the data science process is model analysis and using these models to create hypothesis tests. In this step, we attempt to make various predictions of the databases and visualizations we have gathered using algorithms, linear regression, or any other hypothesis functions/tests.

For our specific case, we have predicted the average view for each game in our database for each month in a chosen 2 years (starting October 2023). Here we have used a gradient descent algorithm to help model and predict certain parameters for a linear regression model.

We want to make it so that we can label each month after 2016 by an integer (1,2,3,...), so

Convert date to number of months (the independent variable) number of months = months after start of 2016

In [25]:
df_tg_modified = pd.DataFrame(df_twitch_games)
df_tg_modified["months_after_2016"] = df_tg_modified["Date"].apply(lambda date_str: 12 * (date_str.year - 2016) + date_str.month)


Now, lets get all the games and set up a new dataframe specifically for modeling our gradient descent algorithm.

In [26]:
all_games = df_twitch_games["Game"].unique()
predicted_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Game", "Month", "Average Viewer Count"])


Lets now define our parameters for our algorithm.

In [27]:
# Define to predict each month for 2 years starting October 2023
PREDICTED_MONTHS = list(range(94, 118)) # <-- change this if you want to change what months to predict
PREDICTED_MONTHS_NP = np.array(PREDICTED_MONTHS).reshape(-1, 1)
# Other prediction criteria
AVG_VIEWS_MIN = 1000
SAMPLE_SIZE_MIN = 30
RAND_SEED = 20
# max_iter = 100 thousand - 1 million for faster but less accurate
# max_iter = 1 million - 5 million are more accurate, but will take significantly longer
# MAX_ITERS = 5000000
MAX_ITERS = 5000000

We have comments to change our parameter specficially for MAX_ITERS. This ranged depending on how accurate we want our prediction to be.

Now we want to count the number of games with certain criterias. We can see that we want the average count to be at least 1000 views, and the game we iterate through's data length to be over a certain amount.

After that, we want to iterate through all of our games meeting a certain criteria. We can use the SGDRegression model from scikit learn to model the behavior in which our criteria-met game average viewer count behaves.

In [28]:
# Count number of games matching criteria (see conditions inside the for loop)
tmp_a = 0
for g in all_games:
    df_tgm_game_only = df_tg_modified[df_tg_modified["Game"] == g]
    if df_tgm_game_only.loc[:, "Average Viewer Count"].mean() >= AVG_VIEWS_MIN and len(df_tgm_game_only["months_after_2016"]) >= SAMPLE_SIZE_MIN:
        tmp_a += 1

print("Processing " + str(tmp_a) + " games... ", end="")

# Go through all games (with a condition mentioned below)
tmp_b = 0
for g in all_games:
    df_tgm_game_only = df_tg_modified[df_tg_modified["Game"] == g]

    # Only process games where average view count in the time period is >= AVG_VIEWS_MIN.
    # And only process games where n >= SAMPLE_SIZE_MIN for a better representative result.
    # (besides, the train_test_split cannot split samples where the sample size is too small)
    if df_tgm_game_only.loc[:, "Average Viewer Count"].mean() >= AVG_VIEWS_MIN and len(df_tgm_game_only["months_after_2016"]) >= SAMPLE_SIZE_MIN:
        # Setup variables
        y = df_tgm_game_only["Average Viewer Count"].to_numpy()
        x = df_tgm_game_only["months_after_2016"].to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1)
        
        x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = ms.train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=RAND_SEED)
        
        # Setup regressor
        sgdr = SGDRegressor(max_iter=MAX_ITERS, alpha=0.0001, tol=0.0001, learning_rate="constant", random_state=RAND_SEED, eta0=1e-7)
        sgdr.fit(x_train, y_train) 
        pred_vals = sgdr.predict(PREDICTED_MONTHS_NP)
        
        # Add each of the rows to the table
        for i in range(0, len(pred_vals)):
            predicted_data.loc[predicted_data.index.max() + 1 if predicted_data.index.max() is not np.nan else 0] = [g, PREDICTED_MONTHS[i], pred_vals[i]]

        # Status print
        tmp_b += 1
        print(str(tmp_b) + " ", end="")
print("\nProcessing completed")
